      <div class="content">
        <p>Not to mention that the feeding the daughter example was an example of an <a href="http://www.dartmouth.edu/~writing/materials/student/ac_paper/logic.shtml#avoiding">either/or logical fallacy</a>.</p>

<p>Presenting two choices when in fact many exist is a weak argument.  Saying either &quot;I write non-free software or my child doesn't eat&quot; is a poor argument.  You can &quot;write free software and have your child eat&quot;.  If people were not eating when they write free software the movement wouldn't have lasted 25+ years.</p>

